{"term": "2011", "caseName": "United States v. Alvarez", "caseLink": "https://www.oyez.org/cases/2011/11-210", "caseTranscripts": [{"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - February 22, 2012", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/22000", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "We'll hear argument first this morning in Case 11-210, United States v. Alvarez.", "start": 0, "stop": 6.73, "duration": 6.73}, {"text": "General Verrilli.", "start": 6.73, "stop": 7.713, "duration": 0.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 7.713, "stop": 10.244, "duration": 2.53}, {"text": "Military honors play a vital role in inculcating and sustaining the core values of our nation's armed forces.", "start": 10.244, "stop": 17.743, "duration": 7.5}, {"text": "The military applies exacting criteria in awarding honors, and Congress has a long tradition of legislating to protect the integrity of the honor system.", "start": 17.743, "stop": 27.472, "duration": 9.73}, {"text": "The Stolen Valor Act continues that tradition by prohibiting knowingly false statements that one has been awarded a military honor.", "start": 27.472, "stop": 35.454, "duration": 7.98}, {"text": "It regulates a carefully limited and narrowly drawn category of calculated factual falsehoods.", "start": 35.454, "stop": 44.31, "duration": 8.86}, {"text": "It advances a legitimate substantial, indeed compelling, governmental interest, and it chills no protected speech.", "start": 44.31, "stop": 53.369, "duration": 9.06}, {"text": "This Court has recognized--", "start": 53.369, "stop": 55.35, "duration": 1.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "General, may I pose a hypothetical?", "start": 55.35, "stop": 58.646, "duration": 3.3}, {"text": "During the Vietnam War, a protester holds up a sign that says,", "start": 58.646, "stop": 64.705, "duration": 6.06}, {"text": "\"I won a Purple Heart -- for killing babies. \"", "start": 64.705, "stop": 69.813, "duration": 5.11}, {"text": "Knowing statement.", "start": 69.813, "stop": 71.548, "duration": 1.73}, {"text": "He didn't win the Purple Heart.", "start": 71.548, "stop": 73.717, "duration": 2.17}, {"text": "As a reader, I can't be sure whether he did and is a combat veteran who opposes the war, or whether he's a citizen protesting the war.", "start": 73.717, "stop": 86.463, "duration": 12.75}, {"text": "Is that person, if he's not a veteran, having received the medal, is he liable under this act?", "start": 86.463, "stop": 93.975, "duration": 7.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think, Your Honor, it would depend on whether that was, that expression, was reasonably understood by the audience as a statement of fact or as an exercise in political theater.", "start": 93.975, "stop": 106.296, "duration": 12.32}, {"text": "If it's the latter, it's not within the scope of the statute, and it wouldn't be subject to liability.", "start": 106.296, "stop": 111.951, "duration": 5.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Somewhat dangerous, isn't it, to subject speech to the absolute rule of no protection?", "start": 111.951, "stop": 119.699, "duration": 7.75}, {"text": "Which is what you're advocating, I understand, that there are no circumstances in which this speech has value.", "start": 119.699, "stop": 125.634, "duration": 5.94}, {"text": "I believe that's your bottom line.", "start": 125.634, "stop": 126.964, "duration": 1.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, what -- what I would say with respect to that, Your Honor, is that this Court has said in numerous contexts, numerous contexts, that the calculated factual falsehood has no First Amendment value for its own sake.", "start": 126.964, "stop": 140.582, "duration": 13.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I'm -- I'm not sure that that's quite correct.", "start": 140.582, "stop": 145.72, "duration": 5.14}, {"text": "It has said it often, but always in context where it is well understood that speech can injure.", "start": 145.72, "stop": 153.699, "duration": 7.98}, {"text": "Defamation, Gertz.", "start": 153.699, "stop": 155.135, "duration": 1.44}, {"text": "At page 12 of your brief, you make this point, and it's what Justice Sotomayor is indicating.", "start": 155.135, "stop": 160.867, "duration": 5.73}, {"text": "You think there's no value to falsity.", "start": 160.867, "stop": 162.96, "duration": 2.09}, {"text": "But I -- I simply can't find that in our cases, and I -- I think it's a sweeping proposition to say that there's no value to falsity.", "start": 162.96, "stop": 172.444, "duration": 9.48}, {"text": "Falsity is a way in which we contrast what is false and what is true.", "start": 172.444, "stop": 177.565, "duration": 5.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I want to be--", "start": 177.565, "stop": 179.783, "duration": 2.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "And--", "start": 179.783, "stop": 180.204, "duration": 0.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I want to respond with precision, Justice Kennedy, that the -- I think what this Court -- and Gertz is a good example -- has done is to draw a line, and that line -- and I think it is Gertz itself that contains this Court's statement that false statements of fact have no First Amendment value.", "start": 180.204, "stop": 198.913, "duration": 18.71}, {"text": "That doesn't automatically mean that a false statement of fact lacks First Amendment protection.", "start": 198.913, "stop": 204.958, "duration": 6.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "--But that's in the context of a defamation case.", "start": 204.958, "stop": 207.676, "duration": 2.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 207.676, "stop": 207.957, "duration": 0.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "And you want to take the Gertz case, where it's well understood that defamation is actionable, and say that as a general matter, that the government can inveigh against what's false.", "start": 207.957, "stop": 220.654, "duration": 12.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "The -- no, I'm trying to say something much narrower than that, Justice Kennedy, that, with respect to factually false statements, the government has the authority, if it can meet the \"breathing space\" principles that this Court's cases have articulated, along with the recognition that factually false statements have no intrinsic First Amendment value -- those are substantial constraints.", "start": 220.654, "stop": 244.94, "duration": 24.29}, {"text": "But they are substantial constraints that are satisfied in this case because the Stolen Valor Act regulates a very narrowly drawn and specific category of calculated factual falsehood, a verifiably false claim that an individual has won a military honor, and that's information that is within -- and only punishes speech about yourself.", "start": 244.94, "stop": 266.54, "duration": 21.6}, {"text": "So it is speech that is uniquely within the knowledge of the individual speaker.", "start": 266.54, "stop": 271.647, "duration": 5.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Suppose -- suppose, General Verrilli, that the decorations were left out and Congress had said: We don't like people saying that they were in the Marine Corps for 25 years when they never served for a single day in any armed force.", "start": 271.647, "stop": 288.67, "duration": 17.02}, {"text": "So they have a statute just like this one, but it is directed to the false claim that one has served in the armed forces.", "start": 288.67, "stop": 302.041, "duration": 13.37}, {"text": "I don't see in your argument that there is something special about the decorations--", "start": 302.041, "stop": 310.035, "duration": 7.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I do think the decorations matter, Justice Ginsburg.", "start": 310.035, "stop": 313.302, "duration": 3.27}, {"text": "We -- we think that that kind of a statute would be a harder case, and under the Court's \"breathing space\" principles closer to the line, because the category is much broader, much harder to define, and it would depend on the interest.", "start": 313.302, "stop": 324.748, "duration": 11.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why is it much harder to define?", "start": 324.748, "stop": 325.562, "duration": 0.81}, {"text": "I don't -- why does the broadness have anything to do with the breathing space?", "start": 325.562, "stop": 329.84, "duration": 4.28}, {"text": "I mean, I suppose your argument here is that there is harm, it's not just falsehood, but it's falsehood conjoined with harm, just as libel is.", "start": 329.84, "stop": 339.402, "duration": 9.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's -- that's exactly our argument, Justice Scalia.", "start": 339.402, "stop": 342.354, "duration": 2.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Okay.", "start": 342.354, "stop": 342.386, "duration": 0.03}, {"text": "So -- and in the example that Justice Ginsburg just gave, in your case there's harm to those courageous men and women who receive the decorations.", "start": 342.386, "stop": 353.471, "duration": 11.08}, {"text": "In the -- in the example that Justice Ginsburg gave, there's harm to the people who honorably served in the armed forces.", "start": 353.471, "stop": 360.315, "duration": 6.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 360.315, "stop": 361.453, "duration": 1.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why isn't that just as--", "start": 361.453, "stop": 362.779, "duration": 1.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And if that -- and if that is -- and that's what I was trying to get to, Justice Scalia, is that--", "start": 362.779, "stop": 366.406, "duration": 3.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Their service is demeaned when everybody says, I served in the armed forces.", "start": 366.406, "stop": 369.186, "duration": 2.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Congress -- under this Court's \"breathing space\" principles, Congress would need to articulate a substantial interest.", "start": 369.186, "stop": 373.355, "duration": 4.17}, {"text": "We think that would likely qualify.", "start": 373.355, "stop": 375.2, "duration": 1.84}, {"text": "We just think that's a harder case.", "start": 375.2, "stop": 376.37, "duration": 1.17}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, where do you stop?", "start": 376.37, "stop": 376.962, "duration": 0.59}, {"text": "I mean, there are many things that people know about themselves that are objectively verifiable where Congress would have an interest in protecting.", "start": 376.962, "stop": 385.069, "duration": 8.11}, {"text": "High school diploma.", "start": 385.069, "stop": 386.38, "duration": 1.31}, {"text": "It is a crime to state that you have a high school diploma if you know that you don't.", "start": 386.38, "stop": 392.47, "duration": 6.09}, {"text": "That's something you can check pretty easily.", "start": 392.47, "stop": 395.126, "duration": 2.66}, {"text": "And Congress can say: We want people to finish high school.", "start": 395.126, "stop": 395.488, "duration": 0.36}, {"text": "It's a big thing to have a high school diploma.", "start": 395.488, "stop": 399.548, "duration": 4.06}, {"text": "So we want to make sure nobody goes around saying they do when they don't.", "start": 399.548, "stop": 402.828, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "What about that case?", "start": 402.828, "stop": 403.608, "duration": 0.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that that case,--", "start": 403.608, "stop": 404.687, "duration": 1.08}, {"text": "Your Honor, I think if it's an objectively verifiable fact -- it would seem more likely that a State legislature might enact a law like that.", "start": 404.687, "stop": 411.964, "duration": 7.28}, {"text": "If it were an objectively verifiable fact and the State could articulate a substantial interest of the kind that Your Honor identified--", "start": 411.964, "stop": 417.369, "duration": 5.41}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "The substantial interest is the one that I've just said.", "start": 417.369, "stop": 419.167, "duration": 1.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--States -- States do have laws, some States do have laws respecting false claims to have received a diploma from a public university.", "start": 419.167, "stop": 428.24, "duration": 9.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that's for submitting resumes.", "start": 428.24, "stop": 429.551, "duration": 1.31}, {"text": "That's -- when -- that's fraud.", "start": 429.551, "stop": 431.66, "duration": 2.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "If I could get back to Your Honor's point about the nature of the harm.", "start": 431.66, "stop": 436.827, "duration": 5.17}, {"text": "It is true that in Gertz you had the particularized harm, but this Court -- the common characteristic that allowed this Court to move from defamation to false light privacy, to intentional infliction of emotional distress in the Falwell case, then to baseless lawsuits, the sham exception in Noerr-Pennington, the sham exception under the National Labor Relations Act, the common characteristic was not an analogy to the particularized harm that existed in the defamation context.", "start": 436.827, "stop": 466.004, "duration": 29.18}, {"text": "The common characteristic that this Court's opinions identify is the calculated factual falsehood.", "start": 466.004, "stop": 471.113, "duration": 5.11}, {"text": "It is true that the harm here is different.", "start": 471.113, "stop": 473.767, "duration": 2.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "They were -- they were in the context, though, of recognized torts, intentional infliction for emotional distress.", "start": 473.767, "stop": 479.967, "duration": 6.2}, {"text": "Here it does seem to me that you can argue that this is something like a -- a trademark, a medal in which the government and the armed forces have a particular interest, and we could carve out a narrow exception for that.", "start": 479.967, "stop": 496.665, "duration": 16.7}, {"text": "I think we would have to do that.", "start": 496.665, "stop": 497.929, "duration": 1.26}, {"text": "But just to say that the cases you mentioned say that there is no value to false speech, I simply cannot agree that they stand for that broad proposition.", "start": 497.929, "stop": 507.802, "duration": 9.87}, {"text": "They do in the particular context of a recognized tort like intentional infliction of emotional distress.", "start": 507.802, "stop": 513.89, "duration": 6.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That -- that is true.", "start": 513.89, "stop": 514.689, "duration": 0.8}, {"text": "And this -- this is a case in which one of the harms that justifies this statute is the misappropriation of the government-conferred honor and esteem, and that is a real harm and a significant harm, and there is also the particularized harm of the erosion of the -- of the value of the military honors confirmed -- conferred -- by our government; and those are particularized harms that are real; and the kind of speech that this statute regulates are a genuine threat to those harms in a way that, looking backwards, looking and anchoring this argument in the tradition of this Court's precedents, this is a type of calculated factual falsehood.", "start": 514.689, "stop": 558.437, "duration": 43.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Harms -- General, I spent a lot of time going through the multiple cases that you cited in your brief defining the various statutes that basically impose penalties for impersonation of some sort or another.", "start": 558.437, "stop": 578.648, "duration": 20.21}, {"text": "And virtually in every one of them, except perhaps one, there was either an economic interest that was harmed by the impersonation, either by the -- by the very face of the statute or by the nature of the claim, a dilution of a trademark, by taking on someone else's valuable property rights.", "start": 578.648, "stop": 608.118, "duration": 29.47}, {"text": "And so I went back reading our cases, and Justice Story many, many years ago said, look, falsehoods have no value as such, but the \"breathing space\" concept is defined by those falsehoods which cause injury to rights that people possess, to -- to pecuniary interests that they have, or to the reputation of others.", "start": 608.118, "stop": 639.871, "duration": 31.75}, {"text": "And almost every statute where we have approved a harm concept as being permissible for recovery has affected one of those three things.", "start": 639.871, "stop": 654.084, "duration": 14.21}, {"text": "So please tell me what's wrong with Justice Story's view, number one; and, number two, how does the definition of harm fit in that?", "start": 654.084, "stop": 670.061, "duration": 15.98}, {"text": "What's the harm here that fits within that descriptor.", "start": 670.061, "stop": 675.466, "duration": 5.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think three points.", "start": 675.466, "stop": 676.827, "duration": 1.36}, {"text": "First, if I could just make a general point in response to Your Honor's question.", "start": 676.827, "stop": 681.9, "duration": 5.07}, {"text": "I think that one reality here is that, as I read this Court's cases, this Court has never held or even suggested in any context when the government wants to regulate a properly defined category of calculated factual falsehood, that it has to meet strict scrutiny.", "start": 681.9, "stop": 700.909, "duration": 19.01}, {"text": "That would be a real break and a real change in the law that would subject--", "start": 700.909, "stop": 706.252, "duration": 5.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I didn't mention -- neither did Justice Story.", "start": 706.252, "stop": 708.187, "duration": 1.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--And -- but -- and again--", "start": 708.187, "stop": 709.391, "duration": 1.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "He said if you want to regulate a falsehood, it has to cause a harm in this way.", "start": 709.391, "stop": 714.765, "duration": 5.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--And that's why I want to get to -- that's -- but I think it's relevant, Your Honor, to the point about Justice Story in the following way.", "start": 714.765, "stop": 721.105, "duration": 6.34}, {"text": "The -- the -- there are a series of statutes, 18 U.S.C. 1001, 18 U.S.C. 962, the impersonating a Federal officer statute, 1001 being the false statement statute; perjury statutes; those are designed to protect the integrity of the government processes.", "start": 721.105, "stop": 739.55, "duration": 18.44}, {"text": "There isn't--", "start": 739.55, "stop": 740.595, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Not really.", "start": 740.595, "stop": 741.628, "duration": 1.03}, {"text": "They are intended to protect the right of the government to secure truthful information.", "start": 741.628, "stop": 745.875, "duration": 4.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Right.", "start": 745.875, "stop": 747.298, "duration": 1.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "The government has a right to subpoena you at trial, subject you to oath, and force you to tell the truth.", "start": 747.298, "stop": 754.606, "duration": 7.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "The statute--", "start": 754.606, "stop": 755.402, "duration": 0.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "So if you -- that's a right.", "start": 755.402, "stop": 756.31, "duration": 0.91}, {"text": "That fits within Story's definition.", "start": 756.31, "stop": 758.619, "duration": 2.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--But not a -- as -- as I read what Justice Story is talking about, he was talking about the rights of private citizens, and what I'm saying is there is an additional category of long recognized, well accepted government regulation of factual -- calculated factual falsehood that serves systemic interests.", "start": 758.619, "stop": 779.925, "duration": 21.31}, {"text": "And, of course, with respect to the Stolen Valor Act, the -- Congress -- Congress is building in the Stolen Valor Act on a statute that Congress enacted in 1923 which prohibited the -- the wearing of medals without justification to wear the medals.", "start": 779.925, "stop": 797.228, "duration": 17.3}, {"text": "And, of course, one of the reasons Congress acted in 1923 to do that was out of concern that the misappropriation of the government conferral of esteem was going to cause substantial harm.", "start": 797.228, "stop": 806.384, "duration": 9.16}, {"text": "That's been on the books for the better part of a century, and--", "start": 806.384, "stop": 811.067, "duration": 4.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is your argument limited to statements that a person makes about himself or herself?", "start": 811.067, "stop": 817.786, "duration": 6.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 817.786, "stop": 818.488, "duration": 0.7}, {"text": "It is.", "start": 818.488, "stop": 819.392, "duration": 0.9}, {"text": "That's the category that the statute regulates.", "start": 819.392, "stop": 822.391, "duration": 3}, {"text": "That is -- and it seems to me in a situation in which the statute is limited to factually verifiable information, the person is speaking about himself or herself, and the category of what's prescribed is clear.", "start": 822.391, "stop": 836.839, "duration": 14.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What's the principal reason for drawing the line there?", "start": 836.839, "stop": 839.323, "duration": 2.48}, {"text": "Suppose the statute also made it a crime to represent falsely that someone else was the recipient of a military medal, so that if someone said falsely and knowingly that a spouse or a parent or a child was a medal recipient, that would also be covered?", "start": 839.323, "stop": 859.814, "duration": 20.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think--", "start": 859.814, "stop": 860.422, "duration": 0.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That would be protected by the First Amendment?", "start": 860.422, "stop": 862.906, "duration": 2.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think that would be -- that would be a case in which under the \"breathing space\" principles that this Court applies when we're talking about calculated factual falsehood, you have to answer a question, which is, how much risk is there of chilling constitutionally protected speech, because when you're talking about somebody else--", "start": 862.906, "stop": 879.804, "duration": 16.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't see any difference as far as that risk goes.", "start": 879.804, "stop": 880.884, "duration": 1.08}, {"text": "I -- I hope that in your earlier colloquy with Justice Kennedy, you -- you were not retreating from what our cases have repeatedly said, that there is no First Amendment value in falsehood.", "start": 880.884, "stop": 895.128, "duration": 14.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--And that only -- and that--", "start": 895.128, "stop": 898.002, "duration": 2.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now this doesn't mean that every falsehood can be punished, because in -- in punishing some falsehoods you -- you risk deterring -- deterring truth.", "start": 898.002, "stop": 907.404, "duration": 9.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--And that's -- that was what I was trying to say in response to Justice Alito's question.", "start": 907.404, "stop": 911.51, "duration": 4.11}, {"text": "You have--", "start": 911.51, "stop": 911.916, "duration": 0.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "I believe that there is no First Amendment value in -- in falsehood.", "start": 911.916, "stop": 914.978, "duration": 3.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--You have to answer the question in that case of whether there was a material risk of deterring expression that's truthful because -- what -- who knows whether your grandfather was telling the truth when he -- when he said he won the medal, and so you -- it may be a more difficult case.", "start": 914.978, "stop": 928.317, "duration": 13.34}, {"text": "But under the Court's \"breathing space\" principles, that's the question that one would have to answer.", "start": 928.317, "stop": 932.517, "duration": 4.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "General, is there--", "start": 932.517, "stop": 933.114, "duration": 0.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, the assumption -- the assumption is that it's false, that was -- and that it's not so hard to find out if somebody claimed to have the Medal of Honor and he doesn't.", "start": 933.114, "stop": 943.779, "duration": 10.66}, {"text": "So that -- first you answered yes, that it's only self, and now you said, no, it can be -- or at least I think you said -- making a false statement of fact.", "start": 943.779, "stop": 957.431, "duration": 13.65}, {"text": "And the concern is -- and I gave you the question of just in the service, leaving out the decorations -- other statements of fact, false statements like", "start": 957.431, "stop": 974.925, "duration": 17.49}, {"text": "\"I deny that the Holocaust ever occurred. \"", "start": 974.925, "stop": 978.811, "duration": 3.89}, {"text": "That's a statement, a false statement of fact, isn't it?", "start": 978.811, "stop": 981.842, "duration": 3.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, it could be.", "start": 981.842, "stop": 983.749, "duration": 1.91}, {"text": "I think a statute seeking to regulate that, Justice Ginsburg, would have viewpoint discrimination problems of the kind that the Court identified in R.A.V., and I think also under the Court's \"breathing space\" analysis you would -- you'd have to look long and hard and have significant concerns about that kind of a -- a statement, because it's so bound up with matters of ideological controversy that -- that you'd want to exercise care, but that's really quite different from what we have here.", "start": 983.749, "stop": 1010.69, "duration": 26.94}, {"text": "This is a pinpoint accuracy, a specific verifiable factual claim about yourself having won a medal.", "start": 1010.69, "stop": 1017.78, "duration": 7.09}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I want to follow up on Justice Scalia's question, because I'm not sure I understood.", "start": 1017.78, "stop": 1021.749, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "The government's position is that there is no First Amendment value in a false representation of fact, by which I understand you to mean not parody or something like that, but a statement that's intended to be understood as true.", "start": 1021.749, "stop": 1037.898, "duration": 16.15}, {"text": "There is no First Amendment value in that statement.", "start": 1037.898, "stop": 1042.413, "duration": 4.52}, {"text": "It may be protected because of the \"breathing space\" argument, but in whatever context, in whatever guise, there is no protection in that false representation as such.", "start": 1042.413, "stop": 1054.221, "duration": 11.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that is the position we've taken in this case, Your Honor.", "start": 1054.221, "stop": 1059.403, "duration": 5.18}, {"text": "The reason we've taken it is because we read the Court's precedents, Gertz and many others, Falwell v. Hustler, as saying precisely that.", "start": 1059.403, "stop": 1066.383, "duration": 6.98}, {"text": "In fact, Falwell goes a step further and says false statements of fact are affirmatively harmful to First Amendment interest because they impede the -- the search for truth.", "start": 1066.383, "stop": 1075.052, "duration": 8.67}, {"text": "That's -- so our -- our position is based on the precise language of cases stretching back a half a century.", "start": 1075.052, "stop": 1082.157, "duration": 7.11}, {"text": "Garrison said calculated falsehood is a category of speech that is no part of the expression of ideas of the search for truth, and then it cites Chaplinsky--", "start": 1082.157, "stop": 1093.696, "duration": 11.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "--General, what about these State statutes -- there are more of them than I thought that there would be -- that say no demonstrable falsehoods by a political candidate in a political race, and prohibit demonstrable falsehoods by political candidates?", "start": 1093.696, "stop": 1109.395, "duration": 15.7}, {"text": "How would your analysis apply to those?", "start": 1109.395, "stop": 1111.205, "duration": 1.81}, {"text": "Would they come out the other end as constitutional?", "start": 1111.205, "stop": 1113.783, "duration": 2.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think that those kinds of statutes are going to have a lot harder time getting through the Court's \"breathing space\" analysis because the context in which they arise is one that would create a more significant risk of chill--", "start": 1113.783, "stop": 1125.496, "duration": 11.71}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, suppose it says demonstrable falsehoods about yourself--", "start": 1125.496, "stop": 1128.62, "duration": 3.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think--", "start": 1128.62, "stop": 1129.825, "duration": 1.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "--just about your qualifications, about what you've done in your life, your -- you know, whether you have a Medal of Honor, whether you've been in military service, whether you've been to college.", "start": 1129.825, "stop": 1138.462, "duration": 8.64}, {"text": "So any demonstrable statement that a candidate, political candidate, makes about himself.", "start": 1138.462, "stop": 1145.349, "duration": 6.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yeah.", "start": 1145.349, "stop": 1146.035, "duration": 0.69}, {"text": "I think under the Court's \"breathing space\" analysis, because of the political candidate context, those statutes are going to pose a particular risk of chill, that this statute does not pose because this is a statute about verifiable factual falsehoods.", "start": 1146.035, "stop": 1159.922, "duration": 13.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "I guess I don't understand why it would be more chilling in the one case than in the other.", "start": 1159.922, "stop": 1161.86, "duration": 1.94}, {"text": "They are the same kind of statement.", "start": 1161.86, "stop": 1163.185, "duration": 1.33}, {"text": "And one knows the same sorts of things about oneself.", "start": 1163.185, "stop": 1167.763, "duration": 4.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think the idea would be, in a situation like that one, the government's power and authority is being trained specifically on the political process and statements in the political process, and this is -- this is quite different.", "start": 1167.763, "stop": 1180.819, "duration": 13.06}, {"text": "This is a statute that says--", "start": 1180.819, "stop": 1183.568, "duration": 2.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I assume that that would be in the case of the State statutes because the State feels that it has a specially important interest in maintaining the political sphere free of lies.", "start": 1183.568, "stop": 1192.846, "duration": 9.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I guess the chilling effect seems to me, at least, to be materially different than in a situation like this one, where what we're talking about is a very specific pinpoint thing, one thing: Have you been awarded a military honor or not?", "start": 1192.846, "stop": 1210.962, "duration": 18.12}, {"text": "And a statement that is about yourself only, not about somebody else, and is supported by a quite strong particularized interest in ensuring the integrity of the military honor.", "start": 1210.962, "stop": 1224.064, "duration": 13.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "I suppose that even in the commercial context we allow a decent amount of lying, don't we?", "start": 1224.064, "stop": 1231.174, "duration": 7.11}, {"text": "It's called puffing.", "start": 1231.174, "stop": 1234.235, "duration": 3.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well--", "start": 1234.235, "stop": 1236.251, "duration": 2.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Although -- although, you know, making false representations to sell a product is unlawful, we do allow puffing, don't we?", "start": 1236.251, "stop": 1248.572, "duration": 12.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well certainly.", "start": 1248.572, "stop": 1250.21, "duration": 1.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "You won't buy it cheaper anywhere else.", "start": 1250.21, "stop": 1252.445, "duration": 2.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's -- that's certainly right.", "start": 1252.445, "stop": 1253.884, "duration": 1.44}, {"text": "But -- and that is the line--", "start": 1253.884, "stop": 1256.321, "duration": 2.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "So maybe we allow a certain amount of puffing in political speech as well.", "start": 1256.321, "stop": 1261.395, "duration": 5.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--And I do think--", "start": 1261.395, "stop": 1262.849, "duration": 1.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Nobody believes all that stuff, right?", "start": 1262.849, "stop": 1264.113, "duration": 1.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I do think the Court's -- I do think the Court's breathing space analysis would call for that, I think that's true.", "start": 1264.113, "stop": 1269.174, "duration": 5.06}, {"text": "But this is a different concept.", "start": 1269.174, "stop": 1271.061, "duration": 1.89}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I suppose it might have something to do with, whether called collateral or not, I mean, I would think the concern in the midst of a political campaign is you have the U.S. attorney or the deputy district attorney bringing a -- filing a prosecution of someone 2 weeks before the election saying, you lied about this or that and maybe there would have to be a deposition or maybe there would have to be a trial.", "start": 1271.061, "stop": 1289.572, "duration": 18.51}, {"text": "Nothing like that is involved here.", "start": 1289.572, "stop": 1290.758, "duration": 1.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Nothing at all, Your Honor.", "start": 1290.758, "stop": 1291.897, "duration": 1.14}, {"text": "And that is what I was trying to say--", "start": 1291.897, "stop": 1293.476, "duration": 1.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, it seems to me your best analogy is the trademark analogy, Olympic case, et cetera.", "start": 1293.476, "stop": 1300.802, "duration": 7.33}, {"text": "You put that in a rather minor -- not as an afterthought, but it's a secondary argument in your brief.", "start": 1300.802, "stop": 1311.063, "duration": 10.26}, {"text": "It seems to me it's the strongest one.", "start": 1311.063, "stop": 1313.828, "duration": 2.76}, {"text": "The whole breathing space thing almost has it backwards.", "start": 1313.828, "stop": 1317.061, "duration": 3.23}, {"text": "It presumes that the government is going to have a ministry of truth and then allow breathing space around it, and I just don't think that's our tradition.", "start": 1317.061, "stop": 1325.682, "duration": 8.62}, {"text": "On the other hand, I have to acknowledge that this does diminish the medal in many respects.", "start": 1325.682, "stop": 1334.584, "duration": 8.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes, and that's the government's interest here, and we do think that that kind of -- I think, Your Honor, that the reason that I think our -- we have a lot of slippery slope type questions here today, but I would urge the Court not to -- not to decline to make a sound decision about this statute based on concern about not being able to draw the line, because this statute is as narrow as you can get.", "start": 1334.584, "stop": 1362.763, "duration": 28.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "General, but I have a problem, which is it's not as narrow as it could get.", "start": 1362.763, "stop": 1365.542, "duration": 2.78}, {"text": "Wouldn't take much to do exactly what Congress said it was doing, which was to protect against fraudulent claims of receiving a medal, and the example it used was someone who used a fraudulent claim of receiving a medal to get money.", "start": 1365.542, "stop": 1384.268, "duration": 18.73}, {"text": "What I'm trying to get to is, what harm are we protecting here?", "start": 1384.268, "stop": 1389.314, "duration": 5.05}, {"text": "I thought that the core of the First Amendment was to protect even against offensive speech.", "start": 1389.314, "stop": 1397.293, "duration": 7.98}, {"text": "We have a legion of cases that said your emotional reaction to offensive speech is not enough.", "start": 1397.293, "stop": 1405.884, "duration": 8.59}, {"text": "If that is the core of our First Amendment, what I hear, and that's what I think the court below said, is you can't really believe that a war veteran thinks less of the medal that he or she receives because someone's claiming fraudulently that they got one.", "start": 1405.884, "stop": 1429.421, "duration": 23.54}, {"text": "They don't think less of the medal.", "start": 1429.421, "stop": 1432.185, "duration": 2.76}, {"text": "We're reacting to the fact that we're offended by the thought that someone's claiming an honor they didn't receive.", "start": 1432.185, "stop": 1441.4, "duration": 9.22}, {"text": "So outside of the emotional reaction, where's the harm?", "start": 1441.4, "stop": 1449.023, "duration": 7.62}, {"text": "And I'm not minimizing it.", "start": 1449.023, "stop": 1451.803, "duration": 2.78}, {"text": "I too take offense when people make these kinds of claims, but I take offense when someone I'm dating makes a claim that's not true.", "start": 1451.803, "stop": 1461.517, "duration": 9.71}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "As a father of a 20-year-old daughter, so do I, Justice Sotomayor.", "start": 1461.517, "stop": 1467.218, "duration": 5.7}, {"text": "But if I could take a minute on the interest, because I do think it's quite important.", "start": 1467.218, "stop": 1471.403, "duration": 4.18}, {"text": "I mean, on some level of course it is true that no soldier charges up Mount Suribachi thinking, well, I'm going to do this because I'll get a medal if I get to the top.", "start": 1471.403, "stop": 1482.135, "duration": 10.73}, {"text": "That's not what the military honor system--", "start": 1482.135, "stop": 1483.62, "duration": 1.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or I'm not going to do this because the medal has been debased.", "start": 1483.62, "stop": 1487.164, "duration": 3.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's not -- well, that's not what the honor system is about.", "start": 1487.164, "stop": 1489.208, "duration": 2.04}, {"text": "The honor system is about identifying the attributes, the essence, of what we want in our service men and women -- courage, sacrifice, love of country, willingness to put your life on the line for your comrades.", "start": 1489.208, "stop": 1505.294, "duration": 16.09}, {"text": "And what the medals do is say to, to our military, this is what we care about.", "start": 1505.294, "stop": 1511.618, "duration": 6.32}, {"text": "It's what George Washington said in 1782 when he set up the honor system.", "start": 1511.618, "stop": 1515.412, "duration": 3.79}, {"text": "It's designed to cherish -- it's designed to cherish a valorous ambition in soldiers and to encourage every species of military merit.", "start": 1515.412, "stop": 1525.021, "duration": 9.61}, {"text": "And what I think with respect to the government's interest here and why there is a harm to that interest is that the point of these medals is that it's a big deal.", "start": 1525.021, "stop": 1533.487, "duration": 8.47}, {"text": "You get one for doing something very important after a lot of scrutiny.", "start": 1533.487, "stop": 1537.125, "duration": 3.64}, {"text": "And for the government to say this is a really big deal and then to stand idly by when one charlatan after another makes a false claim to have won the medal does debase the value of the medal in the eyes of the soldiers.", "start": 1537.125, "stop": 1551.51, "duration": 14.38}, {"text": "It does do that.", "start": 1551.51, "stop": 1552.68, "duration": 1.17}, {"text": "That is the government's interest.", "start": 1552.68, "stop": 1554.368, "duration": 1.69}, {"text": "We think that is a real and substantial interest, and it's threatened here--", "start": 1554.368, "stop": 1557.207, "duration": 2.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the reality here is that this gentleman was publicized, deriled for what he did.", "start": 1557.207, "stop": 1565.44, "duration": 8.23}, {"text": "His public position was compromised, as is the case with almost everyone who's caught at lying.", "start": 1565.44, "stop": 1571.862, "duration": 6.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--But, given that this is a category of calculated factual falsehood, we think the government has the authority and the constitutional -- and the constitutional space to try to deter this kind of speech, as well as allow for private attorneys.", "start": 1571.862, "stop": 1589.118, "duration": 17.26}, {"text": "If I might--", "start": 1589.118, "stop": 1590.057, "duration": 0.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did the military -- did the military ask for this?", "start": 1590.057, "stop": 1592.696, "duration": 2.64}, {"text": "You're claiming there's a special interest in seeing that a military honor is not debased.", "start": 1592.696, "stop": 1601.599, "duration": 8.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It did not, Justice Ginsburg, but under Article I, section 8, Congress has substantial authority to regulate our armed forces, get substantial deference.", "start": 1601.599, "stop": 1613.283, "duration": 11.68}, {"text": "It's not unlike the statute that the Court evaluated in the FAIR case in that regard, which was not a statute that the military -- that the military asked for, but Congress nevertheless was given substantial deference.", "start": 1613.283, "stop": 1624.291, "duration": 11.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did the Commander in Chief sign that, that legislation?", "start": 1624.291, "stop": 1627.949, "duration": 3.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, he did, Your Honor.", "start": 1627.949, "stop": 1628.995, "duration": 1.05}, {"text": "Thank you.", "start": 1628.995, "stop": 1630.43, "duration": 1.44}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Verrilli.", "start": 1630.43, "stop": 1631.508, "duration": 1.08}, {"text": "Mr. Libby.", "start": 1631.508, "stop": 1639.865, "duration": 8.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court: The Stolen Valor Act criminalizes pure speech in the form of bare falsity, a mere telling of a lie.", "start": 1639.865, "stop": 1650.577, "duration": 10.71}, {"text": "It doesn't matter whether the lie was told in a public meeting or in a private conversation with a friend or family member.", "start": 1650.577, "stop": 1655.452, "duration": 4.88}, {"text": "And the law punishes false claims to a military award regardless of whether harm results or even is likely to result in an individual case.", "start": 1655.452, "stop": 1666.761, "duration": 11.31}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What is -- what is the First Amendment value in a lie, pure lie?", "start": 1666.761, "stop": 1672.898, "duration": 6.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Just a pure lie?", "start": 1672.898, "stop": 1674.505, "duration": 1.61}, {"text": "There can be a number of values.", "start": 1674.505, "stop": 1675.288, "duration": 0.78}, {"text": "There is the value of personal autonomy.", "start": 1675.288, "stop": 1678.614, "duration": 3.33}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "The value of what?", "start": 1678.614, "stop": 1679.722, "duration": 1.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Personal autonomy.", "start": 1679.722, "stop": 1681.032, "duration": 1.31}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What does that mean?", "start": 1681.032, "stop": 1682.752, "duration": 1.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that we get to -- we get to exaggerate and create--", "start": 1682.752, "stop": 1685.704, "duration": 2.95}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, not exaggerate -- lie.", "start": 1685.704, "stop": 1686.983, "duration": 1.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, when we create our own persona, we're often making up things about ourselves that we want people to think about us, and that can be valuable.", "start": 1686.983, "stop": 1697.477, "duration": 10.49}, {"text": "Samuel Clemens creating Mark Twain.", "start": 1697.477, "stop": 1701.12, "duration": 3.64}, {"text": "That was creating a persona, and he made things up about himself--", "start": 1701.12, "stop": 1706.399, "duration": 5.28}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, but that was for literary purposes.", "start": 1706.399, "stop": 1709.3, "duration": 2.9}, {"text": "No one is suggesting you can't write a book or tell a story about somebody who earned a Medal of Honor and it's a fictional character, so he obviously didn't.", "start": 1709.3, "stop": 1718.674, "duration": 9.37}, {"text": "It just seems to me very different.", "start": 1718.674, "stop": 1721.189, "duration": 2.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Perhaps.", "start": 1721.189, "stop": 1722.78, "duration": 1.59}, {"text": "But there are other things.", "start": 1722.78, "stop": 1723.81, "duration": 1.03}, {"text": "In addition to the fact that people tell lies allows us to appreciate truth better.", "start": 1723.81, "stop": 1728.248, "duration": 4.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you really think that there is -- that the First Amendment -- that there is First Amendment value in a bald-faced lie about a purely factual statement that a person makes about himself, because that person would like to create a particular persona?", "start": 1728.248, "stop": 1743.273, "duration": 15.02}, {"text": "Gee, I won the Medal of Honor.", "start": 1743.273, "stop": 1746.193, "duration": 2.92}, {"text": "I was a Rhodes scholar, I won the Nobel Prize.", "start": 1746.193, "stop": 1748.162, "duration": 1.97}, {"text": "There's a personal -- the First Amendment protects that?", "start": 1748.162, "stop": 1750.802, "duration": 2.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor, so long as it doesn't cause imminent harm to another person or imminent harm to a government function.", "start": 1750.802, "stop": 1758.859, "duration": 8.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Obvious example.", "start": 1758.859, "stop": 1759.67, "duration": 0.81}, {"text": "Are there Jews hiding in the cellar?", "start": 1759.67, "stop": 1761.546, "duration": 1.88}, {"text": "No.", "start": 1761.546, "stop": 1762.092, "duration": 0.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's right.", "start": 1762.092, "stop": 1765.543, "duration": 3.45}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's not a statement about one's self.", "start": 1765.543, "stop": 1766.795, "duration": 1.25}, {"text": "This is--", "start": 1766.795, "stop": 1768.823, "duration": 2.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "And that's--", "start": 1768.823, "stop": 1769.338, "duration": 0.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are you hiding Jews in the cellar?", "start": 1769.338, "stop": 1769.666, "duration": 0.33}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Excuse me.", "start": 1769.666, "stop": 1770.212, "duration": 0.55}, {"text": "Sorry.", "start": 1770.212, "stop": 1771.148, "duration": 0.94}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 1771.148, "stop": 1773.928, "duration": 2.78}, {"text": "Seems to me that the Stolen Valor Act is more narrow than that.", "start": 1773.928, "stop": 1780.631, "duration": 6.7}, {"text": "And I would say, in that situation, you would not describe what the individual in Justice Breyer's hypothetical was as simply telling a false statement about himself.", "start": 1780.631, "stop": 1794.06, "duration": 13.43}, {"text": "It is about whether there is someone hiding in the attic.", "start": 1794.06, "stop": 1797.527, "duration": 3.47}, {"text": "It is not about himself.", "start": 1797.527, "stop": 1800.183, "duration": 2.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, perhaps, just dealing with an example under the Stolen Valor Act, if a grandfather were to make up a story that he had won a medal in order to persuade a grandchild to--", "start": 1800.183, "stop": 1812.521, "duration": 12.34}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "In order to--", "start": 1812.521, "stop": 1814.022, "duration": 1.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--to join the military--", "start": 1814.022, "stop": 1815.114, "duration": 1.09}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It seems to me that that's missing the limitation that the government has read into this statute: Not damage, not for parody, not to avoid the discovery of someone who should be hidden, not in order to do something with respect to one's grandson.", "start": 1815.114, "stop": 1829.812, "duration": 14.7}, {"text": "It's just a purely false statement about one's self.", "start": 1829.812, "stop": 1833.636, "duration": 3.82}, {"text": "What -- what -- what is the First Amendment value in that, again?", "start": 1833.636, "stop": 1837.777, "duration": 4.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, another value is the fact that the purpose of the First Amendment was a limit on government power.", "start": 1837.777, "stop": 1846.633, "duration": 8.86}, {"text": "It's -- it's -- our founders believed that Congress as a general principle doesn't get to tell us what we as individuals can and cannot say.", "start": 1846.633, "stop": 1855.536, "duration": 8.9}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, of course they do in countless areas, the state does, whether you're talking about defamation, trademark, perjury, all sorts of things.", "start": 1855.536, "stop": 1865.593, "duration": 10.06}, {"text": "You can't adopt that as a general principle and apply it without regard to the situation.", "start": 1865.593, "stop": 1870.873, "duration": 5.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's right, Mr. Chief Justice.", "start": 1870.873, "stop": 1871.949, "duration": 1.08}, {"text": "But in all of those examples, those are examples where we have harm attached to the falsehood.", "start": 1871.949, "stop": 1878.523, "duration": 6.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, sometimes the harm is just impairment of governmental purposes, such as section 1001, which criminalizes the making of a false statement to any Federal agent, for Pete's sake.", "start": 1878.523, "stop": 1891.708, "duration": 13.19}, {"text": "How do you justify that?", "start": 1891.708, "stop": 1894.145, "duration": 2.44}, {"text": "Because the making of the false statement impairs a governmental investigation.", "start": 1894.145, "stop": 1898.844, "duration": 4.7}, {"text": "And what is being urged here is that the making of this type of a false statement impairs the government's ability to honor valorous members of the armed forces.", "start": 1898.844, "stop": 1909.295, "duration": 10.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, we believe there is a difference there, Your Honor.", "start": 1909.295, "stop": 1911.84, "duration": 2.54}, {"text": "With respect to 1001, there's the substantial risk of imminent harm to a government investigation.", "start": 1911.84, "stop": 1917.479, "duration": 5.64}, {"text": "Whether it in fact causes that direct harm, there is still a significant risk of imminent harm resulting from telling a lie to a government investigator.", "start": 1917.479, "stop": 1926.475, "duration": 9}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "But, Mr. Libby, you've suggested to us that we should apply strict scrutiny to all of these cases.", "start": 1926.475, "stop": 1931.018, "duration": 4.54}, {"text": "Now, almost nothing passes strict scrutiny.", "start": 1931.018, "stop": 1932.941, "duration": 1.92}, {"text": "Why should 1001 pass strict scrutiny?", "start": 1932.941, "stop": 1935.815, "duration": 2.87}, {"text": "I mean, it seems to me you're proposing a test that would invalidate all of the laws on the books regarding false statements.", "start": 1935.815, "stop": 1944.094, "duration": 8.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, no, Your Honor.", "start": 1944.094, "stop": 1946.84, "duration": 2.75}, {"text": "What we're suggesting is false statements -- false statements laws do have a history in this country.", "start": 1946.84, "stop": 1952.744, "duration": 5.9}, {"text": "And the Court could recognize a historical category of imminent harm or potential risk of imminent harm to government functions.", "start": 1952.744, "stop": 1961.599, "duration": 8.86}, {"text": "And perjury certainly falls into that category.", "start": 1961.599, "stop": 1964.878, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "1001 very well may fit into that category.", "start": 1964.878, "stop": 1968.564, "duration": 3.69}, {"text": "Since the beginning of our nation, Congress has passed these various false statement laws.", "start": 1968.564, "stop": 1974.92, "duration": 6.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do we give some deference to Congress as to whether there is a harm to governmental purposes or do we make it up ourselves?", "start": 1974.92, "stop": 1982.622, "duration": 7.7}, {"text": "When Congress passed this legislation, I assume it did so because it thought that the value of the awards that these courageous members of the armed forces were receiving was being demeaned and diminished.", "start": 1982.622, "stop": 1997.022, "duration": 14.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well--", "start": 1997.022, "stop": 1997.63, "duration": 0.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "By charlatans.", "start": 1997.63, "stop": 2000.395, "duration": 2.76}, {"text": "That's what Congress thought.", "start": 2000.395, "stop": 2002.439, "duration": 2.04}, {"text": "Is that utterly unreasonable, that we can't accept it?", "start": 2002.439, "stop": 2005.422, "duration": 2.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Justice Scalia, it's not entirely clear what Congress thought here because Congress held no hearings on this.", "start": 2005.422, "stop": 2011.918, "duration": 6.5}, {"text": "It made a broad general finding that false statements -- on the reputation--", "start": 2011.918, "stop": 2015.14, "duration": 3.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, it's a matter -- it's a matter of common sense that it seems to me that it demeans the medal.", "start": 2015.14, "stop": 2020.809, "duration": 5.67}, {"text": "Let me ask you this: What do you do with the statute that prohibits the wearing of a medal that has not been earned?", "start": 2020.809, "stop": 2030.898, "duration": 10.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Wearing medals is a slightly different category because there you're dealing with conduct rather than content.", "start": 2030.898, "stop": 2037.128, "duration": 6.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I'm not so sure.", "start": 2037.128, "stop": 2038.283, "duration": 1.15}, {"text": "You know, the Tinker case with the arm band; it's purely expressive speech, it seems to me.", "start": 2038.283, "stop": 2044.253, "duration": 5.97}, {"text": "I think if you prevail here that the wearing prohibition must also be in serious doubt.", "start": 2044.253, "stop": 2053.109, "duration": 8.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "It may be or it may be in doubt under certain situations where one is wearing a medal.", "start": 2053.109, "stop": 2059.403, "duration": 6.29}, {"text": "But certainly Congress has an interest in protecting non-expressive purposes of wearing the medals.", "start": 2059.403, "stop": 2064.917, "duration": 5.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think it is, the whole purpose of the person who puts the medal on his tuxedo that he didn't earn is an expressive purpose.", "start": 2064.917, "stop": 2075.052, "duration": 10.14}, {"text": "That's pure expression.", "start": 2075.052, "stop": 2077.16, "duration": 2.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "It may be, Your Honor.", "start": 2077.16, "stop": 2080.175, "duration": 3.02}, {"text": "But again, we view it under a different prism.", "start": 2080.175, "stop": 2084.032, "duration": 3.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why?", "start": 2084.032, "stop": 2084.719, "duration": 0.69}, {"text": "I mean, it's expressive.", "start": 2084.719, "stop": 2086.891, "duration": 2.17}, {"text": "One is I am speaking through conduct and the other is I'm speaking through words.", "start": 2086.891, "stop": 2092.592, "duration": 5.7}, {"text": "You wear the medal and you are saying, I am a Medal of Honor winner.", "start": 2092.592, "stop": 2097.057, "duration": 4.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 2097.057, "stop": 2099.088, "duration": 2.03}, {"text": "And as I said, it may ultimately be the case that the Court finds that, if in fact it's unconstitutional--", "start": 2099.088, "stop": 2106.463, "duration": 7.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "So you think wearing--", "start": 2106.463, "stop": 2108.912, "duration": 2.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--this provision, that it could be.", "start": 2108.912, "stop": 2110.304, "duration": 1.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "--that the wearing of a military decoration that you haven't earned, that that's also of questionable consistency with the First Amendment?", "start": 2110.304, "stop": 2121.003, "duration": 10.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "It may be.", "start": 2121.003, "stop": 2122.579, "duration": 1.58}, {"text": "But, again, it would depend on the circumstances.", "start": 2122.579, "stop": 2126.872, "duration": 4.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "No circumstances.", "start": 2126.872, "stop": 2127.952, "duration": 1.08}, {"text": "You go out in the street with the medal on you for everybody to see.", "start": 2127.952, "stop": 2132.811, "duration": 4.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "If -- if there is -- if Congress does not have a non-speech purpose for prohibiting the wearing of the medals, then if it's strictly an expressive purpose, then, yes, there would be a significant First Amendment problem.", "start": 2132.811, "stop": 2148.835, "duration": 16.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, don't you think that's the case?", "start": 2148.835, "stop": 2150.598, "duration": 1.76}, {"text": "There is no non-expressive purpose that I can think of.", "start": 2150.598, "stop": 2154.489, "duration": 3.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well -- and that very well may be.", "start": 2154.489, "stop": 2157.16, "duration": 2.67}, {"text": "What I can say is in this case what we're dealing with is strictly a content-based regulation on speech.", "start": 2157.16, "stop": 2165.422, "duration": 8.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "You acknowledge that the First Amendment allows the prohibition or the regulation of false speech if it causes at least certain kinds of harms.", "start": 2165.422, "stop": 2176.353, "duration": 10.93}, {"text": "And the problem I have with your argument is determining which harms you think count and which harms don't count.", "start": 2176.353, "stop": 2184.07, "duration": 7.72}, {"text": "Would you go as far as was suggested earlier to say that only pecuniary harm counts?", "start": 2184.07, "stop": 2191.347, "duration": 7.28}, {"text": "If you -- if you say that, then the -- the classic case of intentional infliction of emotional distress is unconstitutional, going up to someone and saying falsely, your -- your child has just been run over by a bus.", "start": 2191.347, "stop": 2206.433, "duration": 15.09}, {"text": "So how do we determine which harms are sufficient?", "start": 2206.433, "stop": 2209.873, "duration": 3.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "I believe -- what we believe the right way of looking at this is you -- you determine whether or not there is imminent harm or a significant risk of imminent harm to an individual or to a government function that would result from the speech.", "start": 2209.873, "stop": 2227.273, "duration": 17.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "When you say imminent, you mean -- what do you mean by that?", "start": 2227.273, "stop": 2232.081, "duration": 4.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "I guess I'm suggesting the Brandenburg standard, which is--", "start": 2232.081, "stop": 2238.922, "duration": 6.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, if that's the standard then most of the prosecutions for making false statements to a Federal law enforcement officer are not going to survive, are they?", "start": 2238.922, "stop": 2246.482, "duration": 7.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, but the issue is what about the law.", "start": 2246.482, "stop": 2251.044, "duration": 4.56}, {"text": "And the issue with 1001 and those false statement statutes is the substantial risk of imminent harm to the government that could result from the falsehood.", "start": 2251.044, "stop": 2263.086, "duration": 12.04}, {"text": "So while certainly it may not result in a particular case, but the substantial risk of imminent harm--", "start": 2263.086, "stop": 2269.754, "duration": 6.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, then you're not really talking about imminent harm, I don't think.", "start": 2269.754, "stop": 2273.175, "duration": 3.42}, {"text": "You're just talking about harm.", "start": 2273.175, "stop": 2274.282, "duration": 1.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, when one lies to a government investigator, presumably you're doing it in order to send them in the wrong direction, even if it doesn't do that.", "start": 2274.282, "stop": 2285.387, "duration": 11.11}, {"text": "So the harm may not be there, but there is certainly a significant risk of harm that the government has the right to protect itself from.", "start": 2285.387, "stop": 2294.383, "duration": 9}, {"text": "And that's why we believe that's where you draw the line.", "start": 2294.383, "stop": 2298.135, "duration": 3.75}, {"text": "And that's where this Court appears to have drawn the line in those categories of speech that it has said are unprotected, such as--", "start": 2298.135, "stop": 2305.474, "duration": 7.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Libby, let's suppose that I agree with Gertz that there is no constitutional value in a false statement of fact, and the reason why we protect some false statements of fact is to protect truthful speech.", "start": 2305.474, "stop": 2316.268, "duration": 10.79}, {"text": "So if, if that's so, is -- how is it that this statute will chill any truthful speech?", "start": 2316.268, "stop": 2327.759, "duration": 11.49}, {"text": "What truthful speech will this statute chill?", "start": 2327.759, "stop": 2330.59, "duration": 2.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Your Honor, it's not that it may necessarily chill any truthful speech.", "start": 2330.59, "stop": 2336.947, "duration": 6.36}, {"text": "I mean, it's -- we certainly concede that one typically knows whether or not one has won a medal or not.", "start": 2336.947, "stop": 2344.909, "duration": 7.96}, {"text": "We certainly -- we concede that point.", "start": 2344.909, "stop": 2347.971, "duration": 3.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, boy, I mean, that's a big concession, Mr. Libby.", "start": 2347.971, "stop": 2351.254, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "Then you're saying, you can only win this case if this Court decides that the Gertz statement was a kind of overstatement, an exaggeration, puffery.", "start": 2351.254, "stop": 2363.027, "duration": 11.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well -- we do -- well, we do have the situation where we believe the statute currently does cover: Someone could be prosecuted for engaging in parody or satire or exaggeration.", "start": 2363.027, "stop": 2373.848, "duration": 10.82}, {"text": "Certainly there is nothing on the face of the statute to suggest that those--", "start": 2373.848, "stop": 2378.02, "duration": 4.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the government has said: That's not how we read the statute, and the courts read statutes to avoid a constitutional collision.", "start": 2378.02, "stop": 2393.95, "duration": 15.93}, {"text": "So let's assume that we are not going to cover performances, satire; it's just a baldfaced lie.", "start": 2393.95, "stop": 2402.775, "duration": 8.83}, {"text": "That's all that this covers.", "start": 2402.775, "stop": 2406.554, "duration": 3.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Then it's still our position that it's still a -- that all speech is presumptively protected unless we go back and it fits into one of the historical categories of speech that this Court has found historically is unprotected.", "start": 2406.554, "stop": 2423.438, "duration": 16.88}, {"text": "And there falsity certainly has never previously been recognized by this Court as being an unprotected category of speech.", "start": 2423.438, "stop": 2430.921, "duration": 7.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Counselor, it might--", "start": 2430.921, "stop": 2432.278, "duration": 1.36}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't understand the government to argue that the speech at issue here is totally unprotected.", "start": 2432.278, "stop": 2436.899, "duration": 4.62}, {"text": "I understand them to argue -- I mean, it is totally unprotected.", "start": 2436.899, "stop": 2441.649, "duration": 4.75}, {"text": "I understand them to argue that it can be limited under its \"breathing space\" rationale.", "start": 2441.649, "stop": 2447.989, "duration": 6.34}, {"text": "In other words, it's not within one of the categories of totally unprotected speech.", "start": 2447.989, "stop": 2452.239, "duration": 4.25}, {"text": "You do have to analyze it under the First Amendment and you analyze it to determine if it chills protected speech.", "start": 2452.239, "stop": 2458.876, "duration": 6.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "I suppose I read the government's argument differently.", "start": 2458.876, "stop": 2462.921, "duration": 4.04}, {"text": "As I read the government's argument, it's that it's entitled to, at most, limited protection.", "start": 2462.921, "stop": 2468.918, "duration": 6}, {"text": "So the government seems to start from the presumption that it's not fully protected speech, whereas, of course, what we should be starting with is the presumption that it is fully protected speech unless this Court has previously said it's in one of these historical categories of unprotected speech.", "start": 2468.918, "stop": 2486.131, "duration": 17.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--May I -- if I understood your argument, you're saying historically we have not protected false statements that cause harm.", "start": 2486.131, "stop": 2496.908, "duration": 10.78}, {"text": "I think that's your argument.", "start": 2496.908, "stop": 2499.345, "duration": 2.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct, yes, Your Honor.", "start": 2499.345, "stop": 2501.938, "duration": 2.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 2501.938, "stop": 2502.406, "duration": 0.47}, {"text": "Assuming -- so it's -- we do protect false statements presumptively, but the historical exceptions, like defamation, are those that cause harm.", "start": 2502.406, "stop": 2512.386, "duration": 9.98}, {"text": "So I go back to Justice Alito's question, because you really haven't answered his question.", "start": 2512.386, "stop": 2522.431, "duration": 10.05}, {"text": "You've dealt with the government process cases, although we could argue about whether that's protecting a process or protecting a government right to truthful information.", "start": 2522.431, "stop": 2532.378, "duration": 9.95}, {"text": "That's a different issue.", "start": 2532.378, "stop": 2534.534, "duration": 2.16}, {"text": "But the question is how do you deal with the intentional infliction of emotional distress?", "start": 2534.534, "stop": 2542.17, "duration": 7.64}, {"text": "Because damage, we require injury, and it's defined under law what kind of injury.", "start": 2542.17, "stop": 2550.964, "duration": 8.79}, {"text": "So tell me how you define harm in the nongovernmental situation, number one, and then tell me why that -- this situation doesn't fit that definition.", "start": 2550.964, "stop": 2563.79, "duration": 12.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, in the situation with intentional infliction of emotional distress, you're arguing with an instantaneous harm, a mental distress that results from the false statement.", "start": 2563.79, "stop": 2576.42, "duration": 12.63}, {"text": "So there -- there's imminent harm as a result of -- that results in intentional infliction of emotional distress, a false light false--", "start": 2576.42, "stop": 2585.869, "duration": 9.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "So why isn't the outrage that medal winners, legitimately entitled medal winners, experience in seeing fake people, hearing fake people claim a medal, why isn't that comparable?", "start": 2585.869, "stop": 2599.533, "duration": 13.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, I don't believe that fits into the same category of mental distress that we look at in intentional infliction of emotional distress.", "start": 2599.533, "stop": 2609.672, "duration": 10.14}, {"text": "Certainly people are entitled to be upset by these false claims.", "start": 2609.672, "stop": 2613.684, "duration": 4.01}, {"text": "I mean, I'm personally upset by these false claims.", "start": 2613.684, "stop": 2619.385, "duration": 5.7}, {"text": "But the fact that there is a certain level of upset doesn't mean that you're harmed in the sense of, of the intentional infliction of emotional stress tort, and so what we're dealing with here is simply a non-instantaneous harm.", "start": 2619.385, "stop": 2636.8, "duration": 17.41}, {"text": "Now what the government has suggested is that there is no harm that really results from a single claim; that Mr. Alvarez's falsehood did not cause harm to any individuals.", "start": 2636.8, "stop": 2647.657, "duration": 10.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "It seems to me what you're arguing is that we should determine that there are certain harms that are sufficient to allow the prohibition of a false statement and there are certain harms that are not sufficient, irrespective of what judgment Congress made about the significance of those harms.", "start": 2647.657, "stop": 2666.148, "duration": 18.49}, {"text": "Is that -- is that accurate?", "start": 2666.148, "stop": 2667.287, "duration": 1.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's certainly part of it.", "start": 2667.287, "stop": 2669.318, "duration": 2.03}, {"text": "I mean, we believe that there needs to be imminent harm, that it needs to be targeted harm to an individual or to -- to government function, that it can't be the type of diffuse harm that the government goes to place here--", "start": 2669.318, "stop": 2682.862, "duration": 13.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why not?", "start": 2682.862, "stop": 2684.516, "duration": 1.65}, {"text": "Because, after all, we're willing to protect the Olympics Committee when a false person saying he's the Olympics Committee might deprive the Olympics Committee of a penny, while here they are saying that to win this great medal, say the Congressional Medal of Honor, the highest award in the military the nation can give, you're deserving of the most possible, grandest possible respect, and we don't even want you to have to think about somebody having taken that name falsely, and so we will just criminalize it to discourage such activity that undermines the very thought and purpose of giving the medal.", "start": 2684.516, "stop": 2729.263, "duration": 44.75}, {"text": "All right.", "start": 2729.263, "stop": 2730.498, "duration": 1.24}, {"text": "So I'm just saying in my mind there is real harm, and there is real harm and yet I can think of instances where we do want to protect false information.", "start": 2730.498, "stop": 2739.136, "duration": 8.64}, {"text": "And I want you to accept that as a given because that isn't my question.", "start": 2739.136, "stop": 2743.539, "duration": 4.4}, {"text": "My question is: If I'm right that there are very good First Amendment reasons sometimes for protecting false information, and if this also would cause serious harm that the government is aiming after, are there less restrictive ways of going about it?", "start": 2743.539, "stop": 2764.373, "duration": 20.83}, {"text": "And, if so, what and why?", "start": 2764.373, "stop": 2766.733, "duration": 2.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--There are.", "start": 2766.733, "stop": 2767.31, "duration": 0.58}, {"text": "First of all, more speech.", "start": 2767.31, "stop": 2770.149, "duration": 2.84}, {"text": "There is time to fix the problem.", "start": 2770.149, "stop": 2772.102, "duration": 1.95}, {"text": "If someone tells a lie about having received an honor, there is time for them to be exposed.", "start": 2772.102, "stop": 2777.616, "duration": 5.51}, {"text": "And in fact that's what typically happens--", "start": 2777.616, "stop": 2779.399, "duration": 1.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "The government is going to hire people to follow, you know -- is that realistic?", "start": 2779.399, "stop": 2785.287, "duration": 5.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, what--", "start": 2785.287, "stop": 2787.783, "duration": 2.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "I mean, there is a sanction.", "start": 2787.783, "stop": 2789.284, "duration": 1.5}, {"text": "You know when there is a sanction in place you think twice before you tell the lie.", "start": 2789.284, "stop": 2793.188, "duration": 3.9}, {"text": "But if there is no sanction except you might be exposed, who's going to expose you?", "start": 2793.188, "stop": 2798.124, "duration": 4.94}, {"text": "That sanction already exists, and there are a lot of people nonetheless who tell the lie.", "start": 2798.124, "stop": 2802.999, "duration": 4.88}, {"text": "You really expect the government to hire investigators to go around the country outing people who falsely claim military honors?", "start": 2802.999, "stop": 2814.852, "duration": 11.85}, {"text": "That's not going to happen.", "start": 2814.852, "stop": 2815.851, "duration": 1}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, Justice Scalia, isn't that exactly what's happening right now with this law?", "start": 2815.851, "stop": 2818.663, "duration": 2.81}, {"text": "Because the law is on the books, the law is sending FBI agents out to investigate these allegations.", "start": 2818.663, "stop": 2824.224, "duration": 5.56}, {"text": "How do they find out about it?", "start": 2824.224, "stop": 2825.3, "duration": 1.08}, {"text": "It's because it's reported.", "start": 2825.3, "stop": 2827.519, "duration": 2.22}, {"text": "Individuals hear the statement and they think it may be false.", "start": 2827.519, "stop": 2831.578, "duration": 4.06}, {"text": "They investigate it.", "start": 2831.578, "stop": 2833.439, "duration": 1.86}, {"text": "And -- and, and conduct their own investigations.", "start": 2833.439, "stop": 2836.625, "duration": 3.19}, {"text": "So that's what happens.", "start": 2836.625, "stop": 2839.511, "duration": 2.89}, {"text": "And that's what's supposed -- that's -- that's the whole idea of more speech.", "start": 2839.511, "stop": 2843.571, "duration": 4.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is there anything else -- under that circumstance, that the threat of criminal prosecution might discourage from lying, who would never be caught.", "start": 2843.571, "stop": 2853.768, "duration": 10.2}, {"text": "So at least as to that set, exposure won't work.", "start": 2853.768, "stop": 2858.191, "duration": 4.42}, {"text": "So you have a less restrictive alternative that helps some but not completely.", "start": 2858.191, "stop": 2864.389, "duration": 6.2}, {"text": "Are there others?", "start": 2864.389, "stop": 2865.591, "duration": 1.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, of course if you're never caught, then under the government's theory, then no one has been harmed individually or--", "start": 2865.591, "stop": 2872.107, "duration": 6.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Not under my theory.", "start": 2872.107, "stop": 2874.934, "duration": 2.83}, {"text": "My theory is that it does hurt the Medal, the purpose, the objective, the honor, for people falsely to go around saying that they have this medal when they don't.", "start": 2874.934, "stop": 2886.742, "duration": 11.81}, {"text": "Okay?", "start": 2886.742, "stop": 2886.82, "duration": 0.08}, {"text": "So I might be wrong about that.", "start": 2886.82, "stop": 2890.926, "duration": 4.11}, {"text": "I just ask you to assume that for purposes of argument, because what I'm trying to get to is I want as big a list as I can to think about of what the less restrictive alternatives are, or might be.", "start": 2890.926, "stop": 2903.373, "duration": 12.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Sure.", "start": 2903.373, "stop": 2903.716, "duration": 0.34}, {"text": "The military can redouble its efforts at honoring those who are in fact entitled to the awards.", "start": 2903.716, "stop": 2908.575, "duration": 4.86}, {"text": "There was a Congressional hearing that suggested that the military has been a little lax in identifying true heroes and awarding them medals.", "start": 2908.575, "stop": 2916.869, "duration": 8.29}, {"text": "So that can be done.", "start": 2916.869, "stop": 2918.024, "duration": 1.15}, {"text": "The government can publicize the names of true winners.", "start": 2918.024, "stop": 2922.006, "duration": 3.98}, {"text": "It could create educational programs to let the nation know what it takes to win these awards, what these awards are, who has won them.", "start": 2922.006, "stop": 2928.069, "duration": 6.06}, {"text": "All the heroic activities--", "start": 2928.069, "stop": 2931.053, "duration": 2.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "How about giving a Medal of Shame to those who have falsely claimed to have earned the Medal of Valor?", "start": 2931.053, "stop": 2936.925, "duration": 5.87}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 2936.925, "stop": 2937.221, "duration": 0.3}, {"text": "I think that would be good.", "start": 2937.221, "stop": 2938.017, "duration": 0.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, Your Honor -- actually, that's certainly something the government could do.", "start": 2938.017, "stop": 2942.891, "duration": 4.87}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, not under your theory, right?", "start": 2942.891, "stop": 2944.919, "duration": 2.03}, {"text": "I mean, it's still a sanction for telling something that you say is protected under the First Amendment, whether you get 6 months or a Medal of Shame doesn't matter under your theory.", "start": 2944.919, "stop": 2952.667, "duration": 7.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, there is a significant difference between a criminal sanction that puts someone in prison versus simply exposing them for what they are, which is a liar.", "start": 2952.667, "stop": 2964.694, "duration": 12.03}, {"text": "And Mr. Alvarez, whether or not he in fact was sentenced to a crime, he still was exposed for who he was, which was a liar.", "start": 2964.694, "stop": 2975.316, "duration": 10.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Suppose -- suppose the statute were amended, as has been proposed, to require an intent to obtain anything of value.", "start": 2975.316, "stop": 2987.762, "duration": 12.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "That would turn the law into a fraud statute.", "start": 2987.762, "stop": 2990.059, "duration": 2.3}, {"text": "And of course, fraud is an unprotected category of speech.", "start": 2990.059, "stop": 2994.633, "duration": 4.57}, {"text": "So that certainly would be a constitutional law.", "start": 2994.633, "stop": 2995.963, "duration": 1.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that wouldn't -- that wouldn't reach this speaker.", "start": 2995.963, "stop": 3004.347, "duration": 8.38}, {"text": "Is that -- that wouldn't reach Alvarez, because he didn't obtain anything of value.", "start": 3004.347, "stop": 3009.519, "duration": 5.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's -- I mean, that's not what we have here.", "start": 3009.519, "stop": 3012.205, "duration": 2.69}, {"text": "What we do know is that Mr. Alvarez did not obtain a thing of value.", "start": 3012.205, "stop": 3015.594, "duration": 3.39}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "How do we -- how do we know that?", "start": 3015.594, "stop": 3017.626, "duration": 2.03}, {"text": "He was politically active, right?", "start": 3017.626, "stop": 3019.654, "duration": 2.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 3019.654, "stop": 3019.657, "duration": 0}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Doesn't it help a politician to have a Congressional Medal of Honor?", "start": 3019.657, "stop": 3023.809, "duration": 4.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Perhaps, Your Honor.", "start": 3023.809, "stop": 3026.184, "duration": 2.38}, {"text": "I mean, for -- certainly there are many people out there that would consider that to be a great thing.", "start": 3026.184, "stop": 3033.273, "duration": 7.09}, {"text": "There are also a lot of people out there who don't know what it is.", "start": 3033.273, "stop": 3035.71, "duration": 2.44}, {"text": "And so to them, it might not mean a whole lot.", "start": 3035.71, "stop": 3038.242, "duration": 2.53}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "But it seems to me that your willingness to say that this statute is valid so long as there's some benefit to the person who lies, it's an awfully big concession.", "start": 3038.242, "stop": 3050.268, "duration": 12.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, it would -- if it -- again, if Congress were to amend the law to require that it be done with the intent to obtain a thing of value, again, it becomes fraud.", "start": 3050.268, "stop": 3061.125, "duration": 10.86}, {"text": "And fraud is something that the government does have the right to prosecute.", "start": 3061.125, "stop": 3063.857, "duration": 2.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "So a thing of value, it has to be something of commercial value, right?", "start": 3063.857, "stop": 3066.809, "duration": 2.95}, {"text": "Just to obtain praise and the higher esteem of your fellow citizens, that's -- that's not enough.", "start": 3066.809, "stop": 3078.582, "duration": 11.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Your Honor--", "start": 3078.582, "stop": 3079.959, "duration": 1.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "You have to get a penny out of it, right?", "start": 3079.959, "stop": 3082.63, "duration": 2.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--As I understand the proposed amendment, it just says anything of a non de minimis value.", "start": 3082.63, "stop": 3088.565, "duration": 5.93}, {"text": "How that is ultimately interpreted--", "start": 3088.565, "stop": 3092.251, "duration": 3.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Just a basic definition of fraud in the criminal law.", "start": 3092.251, "stop": 3094.578, "duration": 2.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's right.", "start": 3094.578, "stop": 3095.67, "duration": 1.09}, {"text": "Now, could it -- could it be a nonpecuniary thing of value?", "start": 3095.67, "stop": 3099.48, "duration": 3.81}, {"text": "As it's currently proposed, yes.", "start": 3099.48, "stop": 3102.229, "duration": 2.75}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So if he -- so if he makes this statement at a debate when he's running for office, then you can prosecute him, because getting the office is presumably something of value.", "start": 3102.229, "stop": 3113.534, "duration": 11.31}, {"text": "It presumably has some pecuniary aspect to it.", "start": 3113.534, "stop": 3116.677, "duration": 3.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Perhaps, Your Honor.", "start": 3116.677, "stop": 3119.285, "duration": 2.61}, {"text": "And, again, it may come down to how the courts ultimately interpret a thing of value.", "start": 3119.285, "stop": 3123.89, "duration": 4.61}, {"text": "It's not clear that simply trying to obtain a vote from somebody is necessarily a thing of value, would be considered a thing of value.", "start": 3123.89, "stop": 3133.777, "duration": 9.89}, {"text": "Obviously, if you promise to give up your votes in office in return for support, that would be a little different.", "start": 3133.777, "stop": 3140.589, "duration": 6.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "What if he just gets the cheers of the crowd, he's up there.", "start": 3140.589, "stop": 3144.633, "duration": 4.04}, {"text": "I'm a Congressional Medal of -- the crowd cheers and they give him a parade down Main Street.", "start": 3144.633, "stop": 3149.522, "duration": 4.89}, {"text": "Is -- is that something of value?", "start": 3149.522, "stop": 3151.788, "duration": 2.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "It -- it could be.", "start": 3151.788, "stop": 3154.705, "duration": 2.92}, {"text": "Again, it -- it will come down to over time, how that ultimately gets--", "start": 3154.705, "stop": 3160.465, "duration": 5.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that's not -- the answer is would the First Amendment permit that.", "start": 3160.465, "stop": 3163.479, "duration": 3.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's a difficult question, Your Honor.", "start": 3163.479, "stop": 3169.024, "duration": 5.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's sort of the question we have to answer here.", "start": 3169.024, "stop": 3171.353, "duration": 2.33}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 3171.353, "stop": 3173.15, "duration": 1.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Sure.", "start": 3173.15, "stop": 3173.821, "duration": 0.67}, {"text": "I get that.", "start": 3173.821, "stop": 3175.1, "duration": 1.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Suppose what the person gets is -- is a date with a potential rich spouse.", "start": 3175.1, "stop": 3181.675, "duration": 6.58}, {"text": "Would that be enough?", "start": 3181.675, "stop": 3182.724, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, I think when it comes -- when you get into the situation where you're getting something like a date, I do not know that -- I certainly wouldn't consider that a non de minimis thing of value, but--", "start": 3182.724, "stop": 3197.17, "duration": 14.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Some people might have a different opinion.", "start": 3197.17, "stop": 3201.371, "duration": 4.2}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 3201.371, "stop": 3202.7, "duration": 1.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, that -- that -- and that may be, which is why, should that ultimately become the law, courts would have to look at that very closely.", "start": 3202.7, "stop": 3210.71, "duration": 8.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, how would it work in the law now, where we have similar statutes, and there's an additional requirement when you're imitating, say, a Federal officer or somebody else you shouldn't, you have to perform an overt act that asserts authority that the impersonator claims to have.", "start": 3210.71, "stop": 3228.187, "duration": 17.48}, {"text": "What does that add?", "start": 3228.187, "stop": 3229.123, "duration": 0.94}, {"text": "Does it add enough to just make it not pure speech, to limit -- to wall off the things about -- the things that we're worried about in the First Amendment.", "start": 3229.123, "stop": 3240.179, "duration": 11.06}, {"text": "Or there's another one, you have to falsely assume or exercise powers, duties and privileges.", "start": 3240.179, "stop": 3245.899, "duration": 5.72}, {"text": "Those are ways statutes have of limiting this thing.", "start": 3245.899, "stop": 3250.707, "duration": 4.81}, {"text": "How does that work?", "start": 3250.707, "stop": 3251.752, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, when you get into the issue of impersonation, then you're -- the Court perhaps would be assessing it under the amount of imminent harm to an individual that can--", "start": 3251.752, "stop": 3263.56, "duration": 11.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Nothing to do with harm.", "start": 3263.56, "stop": 3264.621, "duration": 1.06}, {"text": "It's a way of walling off things that are of concern under the First Amendment from those that aren't.", "start": 3264.621, "stop": 3273.133, "duration": 8.51}, {"text": "And what they use -- I read you what they use -- performing -- you know -- you know the language; it's written about in the briefs.", "start": 3273.133, "stop": 3279.068, "duration": 5.94}, {"text": "I just want to know how you would think about a statute that imported that kind of language, which is limiting language.", "start": 3279.068, "stop": 3290.127, "duration": 11.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Jonathan D. Libby", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It would be important, certainly in the First Amendment context, to limit the language as much as possible.", "start": 3290.127, "stop": 3297.326, "duration": 7.2}, {"text": "You want to make it as narrow as possible, because, again, we're supposed to start from the presumption that we -- we have the right to say pretty much what we want to say, and then we start to limit it where.", "start": 3297.326, "stop": 3307.839, "duration": 10.51}, {"text": "Again -- and, I guess, it goes again back to what this Court said in Stevens and Entertainment Merchants, which is, is it one of these historically unprotected types of speech that is not entitled to constitutional protection?", "start": 3307.839, "stop": 3324.017, "duration": 16.18}, {"text": "Unless the Court has additional questions--", "start": 3324.017, "stop": 3330.53, "duration": 6.51}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Libby.", "start": 3330.53, "stop": 3331.454, "duration": 0.92}, {"text": "General Verrilli, you have 3 minutes remaining.", "start": 3331.454, "stop": 3338.777, "duration": 7.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "My -- my only -- one of my questions is the slippery slope problem, college degrees and so forth.", "start": 3338.777, "stop": 3346.526, "duration": 7.75}, {"text": "Could you address that?", "start": 3346.526, "stop": 3347.759, "duration": 1.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor.", "start": 3347.759, "stop": 3349.43, "duration": 1.67}, {"text": "The -- think the \"breathing space\" analysis does a very substantial degree of work in controlling what Your Honor is describing as a slippery slope problem.", "start": 3349.43, "stop": 3362.046, "duration": 12.62}, {"text": "The government's got to have a substantial interest--", "start": 3362.046, "stop": 3362.627, "duration": 0.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "But--", "start": 3362.627, "stop": 3364.175, "duration": 1.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--the statute's got to be narrowly drawn.", "start": 3364.175, "stop": 3365.922, "duration": 1.75}, {"text": "It's got to meet all of those--", "start": 3365.922, "stop": 3367.139, "duration": 1.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "--College degrees.", "start": 3367.139, "stop": 3367.72, "duration": 0.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, as I think I said in my -- in my opening statement, that -- I actually think that's a case in which you could argue that one either way, because there might be, if the government articulated a substantial interest in protecting its--", "start": 3367.72, "stop": 3382.46, "duration": 14.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "How about extramarital affairs?", "start": 3382.46, "stop": 3384.394, "duration": 1.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Excuse me, Your Honor?", "start": 3384.394, "stop": 3385.755, "duration": 1.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "The government has a strong interest in the sanctity of the family, the stability of the family, so we're going to prevent everybody from telling lies about their extramarital affairs.", "start": 3385.755, "stop": 3394.767, "duration": 9.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "In addition to the -- in addition to the governmental interests, Your Honor, there's -- it's got to be tailored in a way that avoids chill, and I think it would be very difficult in that situation--", "start": 3394.767, "stop": 3406.653, "duration": 11.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "This isn't about the person's own experience, that the person knows everything about; you either had one or you didn't have one.", "start": 3406.653, "stop": 3412.353, "duration": 5.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's right.", "start": 3412.353, "stop": 3412.806, "duration": 0.45}, {"text": "And that's a hard case.", "start": 3412.806, "stop": 3413.773, "duration": 0.97}, {"text": "But I do think, with respect to the chilling effect analysis, you -- you would, I think, have a great deal of difficulty sustaining that statute.", "start": 3413.773, "stop": 3422.644, "duration": 8.87}, {"text": "But of course, that's not the kind of statute that we have here.", "start": 3422.644, "stop": 3424.879, "duration": 2.24}, {"text": "This is a targeted statute that's designed to deal with a particular--", "start": 3424.879, "stop": 3430.269, "duration": 5.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "The trouble is you can think of 10,000 instances that meet your criteria that one candidate or another could bring up in a political campaign -- and we don't know what will come up, but I can easily think of examples.", "start": 3430.269, "stop": 3441.576, "duration": 11.31}, {"text": "And then if this is lawful and constitutional, then you have people in political campaigns suddenly worrying that the U.S. attorney is going to come in and start indicting him.", "start": 3441.576, "stop": 3452.367, "duration": 10.79}, {"text": "That's part of the chilling effect.", "start": 3452.367, "stop": 3455.303, "duration": 2.94}, {"text": "And you've assumed you can get around this chilling effect, but I'm less certain.", "start": 3455.303, "stop": 3456.336, "duration": 1.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, I think -- but that's where I think the \"breathing space\" analysis requires before a statute gets upheld that it not have that kind of chilling effect.", "start": 3456.336, "stop": 3466.689, "duration": 10.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "You have to--", "start": 3466.689, "stop": 3467.001, "duration": 0.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--this statute doesn't and that's the key here.", "start": 3467.001, "stop": 3471.158, "duration": 4.16}, {"text": "This statute doesn't.", "start": 3471.158, "stop": 3471.47, "duration": 0.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Counsel, it seems to me that you're asking us to value the speech in context.", "start": 3471.47, "stop": 3475.046, "duration": 3.58}, {"text": "We're not talking about the effect of the speech and whether you can regulate that.", "start": 3475.046, "stop": 3482.135, "duration": 7.09}, {"text": "You're asking us to say, you know, the guy who says he's a college graduate in a political campaign, that could chill political speech.", "start": 3482.135, "stop": 3491.006, "duration": 8.87}, {"text": "So in that lie in that context, you can't sanction.", "start": 3491.006, "stop": 3495.319, "duration": 4.31}, {"text": "But you can sanction that lie in a different context.", "start": 3495.319, "stop": 3500.896, "duration": 5.58}, {"text": "On a date.", "start": 3500.896, "stop": 3501.333, "duration": 0.44}, {"text": "I don't know, because on a date, it doesn't chill political speech, and it will induce a young woman to date someone who she thinks is more of a professional, because that harms the parents, it harms the family.", "start": 3501.333, "stop": 3516.669, "duration": 15.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "May I answer, Mr. Chief Justice?", "start": 3516.669, "stop": 3519.324, "duration": 2.66}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, yes.", "start": 3519.324, "stop": 3520.276, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you.", "start": 3551.484, "stop": 3520.276, "duration": -31.21}, {"text": "The Respondent has conceded that this statute chills nothing.", "start": 3520.276, "stop": 3527.526, "duration": 7.25}, {"text": "That should be a sufficient answer to Your Honor's concern that with respect to other statutes in the future, they can be evaluated to determine whether or not they impose a -- a chill that would lead as an instrumental matter to the conclusion that they ought not to be found to satisfy the First Amendment.", "start": 3527.526, "stop": 3546.298, "duration": 18.77}, {"text": "As Respondent concedes, there is no chill here, so this statute is constitutional.", "start": 3546.298, "stop": 3552.108, "duration": 5.81}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, General, counsel.", "start": 3552.108, "stop": 3553.559, "duration": 1.45}, {"text": "The case is submitted.", "start": 3553.559, "stop": 3554.573, "duration": 1.01}]}]}], "decidedBy": "Roberts Court", "arguedOn": "Feb 22, 2012", "petitioner": "United States", "respondent": "Xavier Alvarez", "docket": "11-210", "citation": "567 US _ (2012)", "justiaLink": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/567/11-210", "lowerCourt": "United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit", "grantedOn": "Oct 17, 2011", "decidedOn": "Jun 28, 2012", "wikiData": {"title": "United States v. Alvarez", "Litigants": "United States v. Alvarez", "ArgueDate": "February 22", "ArgueYear": "2012", "DecideDate": "June 28", "DecideYear": "2012", "FullName": "United States, Petitioner v. Xavier Alvarez", "USVol": "567", "USPage": "709", "ParallelCitations": "132 S. Ct. 2537; 183 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 574; 2012 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 4879", "Docket": "11-210", "OralArgument": "https://www.oyez.org/cases/2010-2019/2011/2011_11_210/argument", "OralReargument": "", "OpinionAnnouncement": "", "Prior": "Defendant's motion for dismissal rejected, unreported, n° CR-07-1035-RGK ([[C.D. Cal.]] 2008); reversed and remanded, 617 [[F.3d]] 1198 ([[9th Cir.]], 2009); rehearing en banc denied, 638 F.3d 666 ([[9th Cir.]], 2011); certiorari granted 565 U.S. ___", "Subsequent": "", "Holding": "The Stolen Valor Act violates the Free Speech Clause of the First Amendment. Ninth Circuit affirmed.", "SCOTUS": "2010-2016", "Majority": "", "JoinMajority": "", "Plurality": "Kennedy", "JoinPlurality": "Roberts, Ginsburg, Sotomayor", "Concurrence": "Breyer", "JoinConcurrence": "Kagan", "Concurrence2": "", "JoinConcurrence2": "", "Concurrence/Dissent": "", "JoinConcurrence/Dissent": "", "Dissent": "Alito", "JoinDissent": "Scalia, Thomas", "Dissent2": "", "JoinDissent2": "", "LawsApplied": "[[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]]"}}